Wash and dry all produce. Preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Trim and discard bottom
woody ends from @asparagus{6%ounce}. Halve @lemon{1}; cut one half into
wedges. Finely chop @chives{1/4%ounce}.

In a #small bowl{}, stir together @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, 1 TBSP chives, and
a squeeze of lemon. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and more lemon (to taste).
Set aside half for brushing the fish and half for serving.

Toss asparagus with a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tablespoon} on a
#baking sheet{}. Season with salt and pepper. Bake in oven until tender and
lightly crisped, ~{10-12%minutes}. Meanwhile, place @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}
in a #shallow dish{} or #plate{} and season with salt and pepper.

Pat @tilapia{11%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{} and season all over with salt and
pepper. Brush all over with half the sauce. Dip one fillet in panko mixture,
coating all over and pressing to adhere. Repeat with other fillet. Heat a large
drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add tilapia and cook
until flesh is opaque and crust is golden brown, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

> TIP: Lower heat if crumbs brown too quickly.

While fish cooks, place @butter{2%tablespoon} and 1 TBSP chives in a small bowl.
Microwave until melted, about ~{30%seconds}. Split @ciabatta bread{2} in half and
brush cut sides with butter mixture. Season with salt and pepper. Place on
another baking sheet and toast in oven until golden brown, about ~{5%minutes}
(you can place them on the same sheet as the asparagus, if there's room).

Cut toasts into triangles. Divide between plates along with tilapia and
asparagus. Drizzle tilapia with remaining sauce. Serve with any remaining lemon
on the side for squeezing over.